7.4.2 Mathematical Model of Enhanced Recurrence

Let the expression level of the targeted plasticity genes be G(t). The change in recurrence parameter \rho is:

\frac{d\rho}{dt} = \eta_{\rho} \cdot G(t) \cdot (\rho_{max} - \rho) - \delta_{\rho} \cdot \rho

where \rho_{max} is the homeostatic ceiling (beyond which network becomes epileptic). The steady-state recurrence is:

\rho_{ss} = \frac{\eta_{\rho} G_{ss} \rho_{max}}{\eta_{\rho} G_{ss} + \delta_{\rho}}

The corresponding increase in \Phi is approximated by:

\Delta \Phi \approx \Phi_0 \cdot \nu \cdot \frac{\Delta \rho}{\rho_0}

For a 20% increase in \rho, with \nu = 1.35, the predicted increase in \Phi is \sim 27\%. Translating to PCI (assuming linear scaling near threshold), this yields a predicted PCI increase of 0.08–0.15 units.

7.4.3 Seizure Risk Mitigation: The Criticality Constraint

The network must remain below the critical point where excitation overcomes inhibition and seizure activity initiates. We enforce a criticality constraint:

\rho \leq \rho_{crit} = \rho_{max} - \epsilon

where \epsilon is a safety margin determined by the local E/I ratio. Real-time EEG monitoring (as in Pillar 1) provides closed-loop feedback: if high-frequency oscillations (HFOs, 80–200 Hz) exceed a threshold, the CRISPRa system is downregulated via doxycycline withdrawal.

