The primary failure mode of circadian engineering is peripheral clock disruption. The SCN drives rhythms in peripheral tissues via autonomic and endocrine signals. Forcing high amplitude in the SCN without preserving the phase relationships among peripheral clocks can cause internal desynchrony—e.g., the liver's metabolic clock running out of phase with the brain's feeding clock, leading to metabolic syndrome (Mukherji et al., 2013).

