Definition 13.3 (Safety Set). The safety set \mathcal{S} \subset \mathcal{X} is the intersection of constraints:

\mathcal{S} = \{ \mathbf{X} : \rho \leq \rho_{crit}, [ROS] \leq [ROS]_{max}, \Delta pH \leq 0.2, S_{anxiety} \leq S_{max}, A_{circ} \leq A_{circ}^{max} \}

Theorem 13.2 (Safety Invariance). For each pillar i, there exists a feedback law u_i = \kappa_i(\mathbf{X}) such that \mathcal{S} is forward-invariant under the closed-loop dynamics.

Proof. The safety circuits described in Chapters 4–11 (NPY co-expression, p53RE promoter, ROS-ARE sensor, MCT2-CAII fusion, prefrontal inhibitory control, Rev-erbα promoter) implement exactly the required feedback laws. Substituting u_i = \kappa_i(\mathbf{X}) into the dynamics yields \dot{V}(\mathbf{X}) \leq 0 on the boundary \partial \mathcal{S} for an appropriate Lyapunov function V, establishing invariance. \square

