CHAPTER 15: AXIOMATIC ETHICAL ARCHITECTURE

15.1 Introduction

This chapter presents the ethical architecture of the Carbon-First framework as a set of axioms and theorems that are part of the formal design specification. No policy recommendations, regulatory pathways, or implementation scenarios are described. The content is purely normative mathematics: definitions of safety constraints, proofs of reversibility, and formal equity conditions.

15.2 Axioms of Carbon-First Ethics

Axiom 15.1 (Somatic-Only Principle). All interventions \mathbf{u} \in \mathcal{U} satisfy \partial \mathcal{G} / \partial \mathbf{u} = 0, where \mathcal{G} is the germline state vector.

Axiom 15.2 (Reversibility Principle). For any intervention vector \mathbf{u}, there exists a reversal operator \mathcal{R} such that \mathcal{R} \circ \mathcal{D}(\mathbf{u}) = \mathcal{I} within finite time \tau_{rev} < \infty.

Axiom 15.3 (Safety Supremacy Principle). For any intervention sequence, the safety constraints \mathcal{S} take lexical priority over the optimization objective \mathcal{J}. Formally, if \mathbf{X}(t) \notin \mathcal{S}, then \mathbf{u} is modified such that \mathbf{X}(t) \in \mathcal{S} regardless of \mathcal{J}.

Axiom 15.4 (Wisdom-Integration Principle). Any admissible intervention must satisfy B_{int} \geq B_{int}^0; interoceptive precision shall not be reduced.

Axiom 15.5 (Equity Axiom). The distribution of access to interventions, denoted by probability measure \mu over population \mathcal{P}, must satisfy:

\frac{\mu(A | \text{high SES})}{\mu(A | \text{low SES})} \leq R_{max}

where A is the event of receiving intervention, and R_{max} is the maximal allowable inequality ratio.

15.3 Theorems of Ethical Architecture

15.3.1 Reversibility Theorem

Theorem 15.1 (CRISPRa Reversibility). For any pillar i \in \{1,2,4,5,6,7,8\} using CRISPRa, the reversal operator \mathcal{R} consisting of CRISPRi delivery or doxycycline withdrawal satisfies:

\| \mathbf{X}(t) - \mathbf{X}_0 \| \leq \varepsilon \quad \forall t \geq \tau_{rev}

with \tau_{rev} \leq 14 days and \varepsilon arbitrarily small.

Proof. The dCas9-activator degrades with half-life \tau_{1/2} \approx 24 h. The epigenetic marks revert with half-life 3–7 days. Solving the linear decay ODE yields \mathbf{X}(t) = \mathbf{X}_0 + (\mathbf{X}(0) - \mathbf{X}_0) e^{-t/\tau_{eff}}. For t \geq 5\tau_{eff} \approx 14 days, the error is below 1%. \square

15.3.2 Safety Invariance Theorem

Theorem 15.2 (Safety Circuit Invariance). For each pillar i, the safety circuit s_i(\mathbf{X}) ensures that the trajectory \mathbf{X}(t) remains within \mathcal{S} for all t \geq 0 provided the initial state \mathbf{X}_0 \in \mathcal{S}.

Proof. Each safety circuit implements a barrier function B_i(\mathbf{X}) such that \dot{B}_i \leq 0 when \mathbf{X} approaches the boundary of \mathcal{S}. This is verified for each pillar in its respective chapter:

· P1: NPY co-expression bounds E/I ratio.
· P3: p53RE promoter restricts Dsup to damage states.
· P5: ROS-ARE sensor downregulates PGC-1α4.
· P6: MCT2-CAII fusion prevents acidosis.
· P4,7,8: Criticality, inhibitory control, and phase-restriction maintain stability.

By Nagumo's theorem, \mathcal{S} is forward-invariant. \square

15.3.3 Equity Feasibility Theorem

Theorem 15.3 (Existence of Equitable Distribution). Under the open-source DNA architecture axiom, there exists a resource allocation policy \pi such that the equity constraint R \leq R_{max} is satisfiable for R_{max} \geq 1.

Proof. The open-source axiom eliminates intellectual property barriers, reducing the marginal cost of intervention to the cost of vector production and administration. Let C be the per-capita cost. A progressive subsidy scheme funded by a solidarity levy on market-rate interventions can achieve any desired ratio R by redistributing resources from high-SES to low-SES recipients. The existence of such a scheme follows from the convexity of the cost function and the linearity of the subsidy transfer. \square

